---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

// Services — three packages as plain articles, equal visual weight,
// no "best value" hierarchy. Pricing held for the Discovery Call.
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Services"
  description="How Stacey works — the Discovery Call, what a session looks like, and the ways to work together."
>
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="process-heading">
    <div class="column">
      <h1 id="process-heading">How Stacey works</h1>

      <p>
        Every working relationship starts with a Discovery Call &mdash;
        free, twenty to thirty minutes, no pressure to continue.
        You'll come away knowing whether you want to.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you keep going, the sessions feel like an unhurried
        Friday afternoon. Plain language, a few things at a time.
        Once those are clear the rest tends to settle.
      </p>

      <p><em>&ldquo;Let's look at the real numbers.&rdquo;</em></p>

      <p>
        You leave with a clearer picture and one or two concrete
        next steps. The rest can wait until the next session.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="packages-heading">
    <div class="column-wide">
      <h2 id="packages-heading">Ways to work together</h2>

      <p>
        The Discovery Call is always free. From there, the work
        usually takes one of a few shapes &mdash; you don't have to
        pick the right one in advance.
      </p>

      <article class="pathway" style="margin-top: 3rem;">
        <h3>Clarity Session</h3>
        <p class="pathway__price">$197 &middot; up to ninety minutes</p>
        <p>
          One ninety-minute conversation. You bring whatever you can
          find &mdash; recent statements, a rough sense of income, the
          bills you know about &mdash; and we look at all of it
          together.
        </p>
        <p class="pathway__for">
          For when you want one clear look at where you are and a
          couple of concrete next steps, without committing to more.
        </p>
        <ul class="pathway__includes">
          <li>One ninety-minute session</li>
          <li>Walk through your current picture together</li>
          <li>Short written summary in your inbox within forty-eight hours</li>
          <li>No ongoing commitment</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="pathway" style="margin-top: 3rem;">
        <h3>Fresh Start</h3>
        <p class="pathway__price">$397 &middot; up to three hours total</p>
        <p>
          A Clarity Session plus a sixty-minute follow-up a few weeks
          later, to work through what came up between conversations.
        </p>
        <p class="pathway__for">
          For when one conversation isn't quite enough &mdash; usually
          because real life intervenes between sessions and a second
          look helps land the first.
        </p>
        <ul class="pathway__includes">
          <li>Everything in the Clarity Session</li>
          <li>Sixty-minute follow-up a few weeks later</li>
          <li>Personalised roadmap document you can refer back to</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="pathway" style="margin-top: 3rem;">
        <h3>Complete Blueprint</h3>
        <p class="pathway__price">$697 &middot; up to six hours total</p>
        <p>
          Four sessions over a couple of months for people sorting
          through more than one thing at once.
        </p>
        <p class="pathway__for">
          For when more than one piece is in motion &mdash; a divorce
          alongside retirement planning, a late start with debt to
          untangle, a caregiving load that's changed the picture.
        </p>
        <ul class="pathway__includes">
          <li>Four sessions, one at a time</li>
          <li>A real plan for debt and savings</li>
          <li>Retirement projection (if retirement is close)</li>
          <li>Thirty days of email support between sessions</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="pathway" style="margin-top: 3rem;">
        <h3>Full Year</h3>
        <p class="pathway__price">$1,697 &middot; up to ten hours total</p>
        <p>
          Quarterly check-ins across twelve months, for people who'd
          rather have Stacey as the person they check in with
          regularly as life changes.
        </p>
        <p class="pathway__for">
          For when life keeps moving &mdash; kids leaving home, a
          parent needing care, a retirement starting to take shape
          &mdash; and a steady quarterly conversation is more useful
          than a one-time plan.
        </p>
        <ul class="pathway__includes">
          <li>Everything in Complete Blueprint</li>
          <li>Quarterly check-ins for twelve months</li>
          <li>Annual review</li>
          <li>Email support all year</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <p style="margin-top: 3rem;">
        All fees are flat &mdash; paid once per package, nothing on
        commission, no percentage of anything. If you're not sure
        which fits, <a href="/contact">book a free Discovery Call</a>
        and we'll work it out together.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    /* Pathway price line — small italic caption sitting right under
       the h3. Transparent pricing without a card-style price badge
       (Pass 469 — punch-list #3). Same muted-ink color as the
       other supporting type so it reads as info, not marketing. */
    .pathway__price {
      font-style: italic;
      color: var(--c-ink-soft);
      font-size: 1rem;
      margin-top: -0.25rem;
      margin-bottom: 0.875rem;
      font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums;
    }

    /* Pathway "what's included" lists — paper-aesthetic bullets in
       muted gold, indented modestly, no card grid. Scannable detail
       without the SaaS-feature-list energy. */
    .pathway__for {
      font-style: italic;
      color: var(--c-ink-soft);
      max-width: var(--measure-prose);
      margin-top: 0.5rem;
      margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    }
    .pathway__includes {
      list-style: none;
      padding: 0;
      margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0;
    }
    .pathway__includes li {
      position: relative;
      padding: 0.25rem 0 0.25rem 1.5rem;
      color: var(--c-ink-soft);
      font-size: 1rem;
      line-height: 1.55;
      max-width: var(--measure-prose);
    }
    .pathway__includes li::before {
      content: "";
      position: absolute;
      left: 0.25rem;
      top: 0.85rem;
      width: 0.625rem;
      height: 0.625rem;
      border-radius: 999px;
      background-color: var(--c-gold);
      opacity: 0.5;
    }

    /* Emotional-hesitation FAQ. <dl> for correct semantics; styled
       so the questions read as quiet thoughts rather than support-
       documentation headings. No toggles, no chevrons — the whole
       list is always open so reading stays continuous. */
    .faq {
      margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0;
      max-width: var(--measure-prose);
    }
    .faq dt {
      font-style: italic;
      color: var(--c-ink);
      margin-top: 1.5rem;
      margin-bottom: 0.375rem;
    }
    .faq dt:first-of-type {
      margin-top: 0;
    }
    .faq dd {
      margin: 0;
      color: var(--c-ink-soft);
    }
  </style>

  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="wondering-heading">
    <div class="column">
      <h2 id="wondering-heading">If you're wondering</h2>

      <dl class="faq">
        <dt>What if I'm embarrassed about where things are?</dt>
        <dd>
          <em>&ldquo;That feeling is exactly why you need this conversation.&rdquo;</em>
          Most people are embarrassed. The point of sitting down with
          Stacey isn't to be impressed by how organized you are. It's
          to put the embarrassment down for an hour.
        </dd>

        <dt>What if I don't know what to ask?</dt>
        <dd>
          You don't need to. Stacey asks the questions. You answer the
          ones that fit your life and skip the ones that don't.
        </dd>

        <dt>What if my situation feels too messy to explain?</dt>
        <dd>
          You don't have to explain it in advance. The Discovery Call
          is for a rough sense of where you are &mdash; a thirty-second
          version is enough. The detail comes later, in sessions,
          with time.
        </dd>

        <dt>What if I just need someone to help me think clearly?</dt>
        <dd>
          That's most of what Stacey does. Not optimizing returns;
          just being a steady second mind on what's already there.
        </dd>
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="not-heading">
    <div class="column">
      <h2 id="not-heading">What this isn't</h2>

      <p>
        Stacey isn't licensed to give investment advice, recommend
        specific securities, manage your money, or hold it on your
        behalf. She doesn't sell products, take a percentage of
        anything, or work on commission from anyone.
      </p>

      <p>
        She charges a flat fee for her time. That's the whole
        arrangement. The relationship is between her and you, with
        nobody in the middle.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
